## 9. ATT - Attribute Protocol {#att}

### 9.1 Attribute Protocol {#attribute-protocol}

ATT is the wire protocol for reading/writing GATT attributes. It defines how to structure and transmit attribute data.

---

### 9.2 ATT Error Codes {#att-error-codes}

When an ATT operation fails, the server responds with an error code:

| Error Code | Meaning |
|-----------|---------|
| 0x00 | Success |
| 0x01 | Invalid Handle |
| 0x02 | Read Not Permitted |
| 0x03 | Write Not Permitted |
| 0x04 | Invalid PDU |
| 0x05 | Insufficient Authentication |
| 0x06 | Insufficient Authorization |
| 0x07 | Insufficient Encryption Key Size |
| 0x08 | Insufficient Encryption |
| 0x0C | Insufficient Resources |

---

### 9.3 ATT Operations - Complete Reference {#att-operations}

**ATT defines 31 different operation types.** Here are the most common:

| Operation | Format | Uses |
|-----------|--------|------|
| **Exchange MTU Request** | [Client ATT-size] → [Server ATT-size] | Negotiate attribute data size |
| **Find Information Request** | [Start-handle, End-handle] | Discover all attributes in a range |
| **Find By Type Request** | [Start-handle, End-handle, Type-UUID, Value] | Search for attributes by type and value |
| **Read Request** | [Handle] | Read a single attribute |
| **Read Blob Request** | [Handle, Offset] | Read partial data from an attribute |
| **Read Multiple Request** | [Handle1, Handle2, ...] | Read multiple attributes at once |
| **Read By Type Request** | [Start-handle, End-handle, Type-UUID] | Find all attributes of a given type |
| **Write Request** | [Handle, Value] | Write an attribute (expects response) |
| **Write Command** | [Handle, Value] | Write an attribute (no response) |
| **Notify** | [Handle, Value] | Server pushes data to client |
| **Indicate** | [Handle, Value] | Server pushes data to client (guaranteed) |

---

### 9.4 ATT MTU Negotiation {#att-mtu}

**MTU = Maximum Transmission Unit**

Default ATT MTU = 27 bytes per transaction. Larger MTU = fewer transactions for large data.

Both sides propose their MTU during connection. The smaller of the two is used.

